# Terraform Google Cloud Provider

The Google Cloud provider (`hashicorp/google`) lets you manage GCP infrastructure declaratively with Terraform. It supports Compute Engine, Cloud Storage, Cloud SQL, GKE, Cloud Run, IAM, networking, and hundreds of other GCP resource types.

## Provider Configuration

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    google = {
      source  = "hashicorp/google"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "google" {
  project = "my-project-id"
  region  = "us-central1"
  zone    = "us-central1-a"
}
```

The `project`, `region`, and `zone` arguments set defaults for all resources. They can also be set via environment variables `GOOGLE_PROJECT`, `GOOGLE_REGION`, and `GOOGLE_ZONE`, or overridden per resource.

### Google Beta Provider

Some GCP features are available in beta before general availability. Use the `google-beta` provider for these:

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    google-beta = {
      source  = "hashicorp/google-beta"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "google-beta" {
  project = "my-project-id"
  region  = "us-central1"
}

resource "google_compute_instance" "beta_feature" {
  provider = google-beta
  # ... resource config using beta features
}
```

## Authentication

The Google provider resolves credentials using Application Default Credentials (ADC) in this order:

1. **GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS** — environment variable pointing to a service account key JSON file
2. **gcloud auth application-default login** — user credentials stored by the gcloud CLI
3. **Service account key file** — path specified in the `credentials` argument
4. **Workload Identity Federation** — OIDC-based authentication for CI/CD (GitHub Actions, GitLab)
5. **Compute Engine metadata** — automatic on GCE instances, Cloud Build, Cloud Run

```bash
# Option 1: Service account key file
export GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS="/path/to/service-account-key.json"

# Option 2: gcloud user credentials (for local development)
gcloud auth application-default login

# Option 3: Set project via gcloud
gcloud config set project my-project-id
```

```hcl
# Explicit credentials file in provider block (not recommended for production)
provider "google" {
  project     = "my-project-id"
  region      = "us-central1"
  credentials = file("service-account-key.json")
}
```

For CI/CD, prefer Workload Identity Federation over service account keys to avoid managing long-lived secrets.

## Common Resources

```hcl
# Compute Engine instance
resource "google_compute_instance" "web" {
  name         = "web-server"
  machine_type = "e2-micro"
  zone         = "us-central1-a"

  boot_disk {
    initialize_params {
      image = "debian-cloud/debian-12"
      size  = 20
    }
  }

  network_interface {
    network    = google_compute_network.vpc.id
    subnetwork = google_compute_subnetwork.subnet.id

    access_config {
      # Assigns an ephemeral external IP
    }
  }

  metadata_startup_script = "apt-get update && apt-get install -y nginx"

  tags = ["http-server", "https-server"]
}

# Cloud Storage bucket
resource "google_storage_bucket" "assets" {
  name          = "my-app-assets-${var.environment}"
  location      = "US"
  force_destroy = false

  uniform_bucket_level_access = true

  versioning {
    enabled = true
  }

  lifecycle_rule {
    condition {
      age = 90
    }
    action {
      type = "Delete"
    }
  }
}

# Cloud SQL instance
resource "google_sql_database_instance" "postgres" {
  name             = "app-db"
  database_version = "POSTGRES_16"
  region           = "us-central1"

  settings {
    tier = "db-f1-micro"

    ip_configuration {
      ipv4_enabled    = true
      private_network = google_compute_network.vpc.id
    }

    backup_configuration {
      enabled    = true
      start_time = "03:00"
    }
  }

  deletion_protection = true
}

# GKE cluster
resource "google_container_cluster" "primary" {
  name     = "primary-cluster"
  location = "us-central1"

  initial_node_count       = 1
  remove_default_node_pool = true

  network    = google_compute_network.vpc.id
  subnetwork = google_compute_subnetwork.subnet.id
}

resource "google_container_node_pool" "primary_nodes" {
  name       = "primary-node-pool"
  cluster    = google_container_cluster.primary.id
  node_count = 3

  node_config {
    machine_type = "e2-standard-2"
    oauth_scopes = [
      "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform"
    ]
  }
}

# Cloud Run service
resource "google_cloud_run_service" "api" {
  name     = "api-service"
  location = "us-central1"

  template {
    spec {
      containers {
        image = "gcr.io/my-project/api:latest"
        ports {
          container_port = 8080
        }
        resources {
          limits = {
            memory = "512Mi"
            cpu    = "1000m"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  traffic {
    percent         = 100
    latest_revision = true
  }
}

# IAM member binding
resource "google_project_iam_member" "editor" {
  project = var.project_id
  role    = "roles/editor"
  member  = "serviceAccount:${google_service_account.sa.email}"
}

# VPC network
resource "google_compute_network" "vpc" {
  name                    = "main-vpc"
  auto_create_subnetworks = false
}

resource "google_compute_subnetwork" "subnet" {
  name          = "main-subnet"
  ip_cidr_range = "10.0.0.0/24"
  region        = "us-central1"
  network       = google_compute_network.vpc.id
}
```

## Data Sources

Data sources query existing GCP resources without managing them:

```hcl
# Current project metadata
data "google_project" "current" {}

output "project_number" {
  value = data.google_project.current.number
}

# Existing VPC network
data "google_compute_network" "existing" {
  name = "default"
}

# Current client config (useful for GKE auth)
data "google_client_config" "current" {}

output "access_token" {
  value     = data.google_client_config.current.access_token
  sensitive = true
}

# Available compute zones
data "google_compute_zones" "available" {
  region = "us-central1"
}
```

The `google_client_config` data source is especially useful for configuring the Kubernetes provider to authenticate with a GKE cluster.

## Project and Region Configuration

Resources inherit `project`, `region`, and `zone` from the provider block, but they can be overridden per resource:

```hcl
resource "google_storage_bucket" "eu_data" {
  name     = "eu-data-bucket"
  project  = "other-project-id"
  location = "EU"
}
```

Use variables for project and region to support multiple environments:

```hcl
variable "project_id" {
  type = string
}

variable "region" {
  type    = string
  default = "us-central1"
}

provider "google" {
  project = var.project_id
  region  = var.region
}
```
